title: Really good phone, way better than expected
text:
I really like this phone. The battery life is superb. The performance is like greased lightning. The picture is excellent. The voice quality is great. The fingerprint reader is so far nearly flawless, and very easy to use with the sensor being in the back. (I haven't played with the camera much myself, can't say anything useful about that.) Everyone in my family switched to Pixel3 phones recently (models include P3A, P3, P3XL), and all are very satisfied. BTW, the pink isn't very pink, and I use a cover anyway, so I don't notice it.

I particularly like the absence of bloatware (a less polite word for it is generally used) on the Google devices, it's been really pleasant not to have to spend a few hours uninstalling or disabling all those lovely apps the carriers and vendors love to stuff into your phone to make sure your memory and bandwidth are being properly used.

I have just one complaint, and that is the absence of a memory expansion port. I'd love to be able to stick a 128gb sd card (or maybe even 256gb) for media files and application data, to be able to hold tons of media files.

title: Works well, charges phone fast
text: This is a pretty decent charger, works well with my Pixel 3 phone. It's particularly useful to have the dual charge slots, either for a passenger or for a second device.  I'm considering getting more for the other cars in the family, which are still equipped with the older USB chargers.

title: Not particularly sturdy or shock-absorbing, just a soft cover
text: I didn't expect much for this low price, and so wasn't disappointed. The description is a bit inflated, but if you're just looking for a soft cover that makes the phone easier to hold and offers protection against minor scratces, you won't be disappointed.  If you want more protection, I suggest looking at something else, such as an Otterbox.

title: Not bad, but unfortunately not stellar
text:
Good idea, but underachieved in the end result. I mostly compared this phone with my (now old) Samsung S4, and in comparison the P8 disappoints. The S4 is a superior device in just about every way: better graphics, better software design (especially ease of use), better sound, etc. For example, I found it frustratingly difficult to get the right zoom level for a photograph. And after I took several pictures, I found it quite difficult to review all the pictures, and delete the ones I didn't want. It would seem obvious to be able to delete (or do something else) to a picture that I'm viewing ... well, not the way Huawei designers thought about it. All the controls and options seem just a tad less smooth than you'd want in a good smartphone.

For sound and visuals, the best way I can put it is that the P8 sounds a bit tinny and sort of looks it, too (if you can mentally translate the idea of tinny to visuals). If you check the published specs and/or read published reviews, you'll see the detailed differences, so I won't bother to repeat them here. Suffice it to say that 720x1280 just isn't good enough for a phone priced in this range.

All the usual Google/Android apps work as expected, I didn't see anything particularly different about them, although I found the phone's responsiveness to touch and swipe and long-press less than ideal. I've used both Samsung and Apple devices recently, and there's a reason why those two brands are so popular.

That said, it's not a bad phone, and a perfectly reasonable option as your unlocked phone for international travel, for instance. (So that you can buy a prepaid chip locally and use a phone without paying ridiculous roaming charges.) But before you buy this one, check for alternatives, there are a few others worth considering (such as a Nokia Lumia, a Moto E, or even an Amazon Fire Phone perhaps).

title: fits s4 perfectly, provides good protection
text: This case is definitely not soft, the back feels quite firm and hard.  However, it goes on and comes off without difficulty, and has all the right shapes and holes for the S4 buttons and holes.  I find it to be better than the Samsung-branded case of the same type -- it seems to provide better protection (I didn't do a drop test) and makes it comfortable to hold the phone.

title: reasonable quality cover for the price, not cushioned
text:
If you're looking for a protective cover, but don't need the shock protection of the "bumper" covers, then this one is a good option. It fits my S4 well, providing some protection for the back and a cover for the front to prevent scratches (e.g., in a briefcase or purse). Just what I needed for my purposes.

If you are looking to trick out your phone, however, then you might be disappointed. Stylish this isn't.

title: attractive, easy to pair, great sound quality
text:
I have to admit that the first thing that struck me about this headset was how attractively designed it was. At the same time, it's large compared to my BlueAnt Z9, seems similar to the old Plantronics Voyager. If you like a headset that goes over the ear and feels like it will just stay there, while being quite comfortable, then this one is definitely worth a try.

Pairing with an Android phone was very easy, took less than 10 seconds (I think) after glancing through the easy start guide. The sound quality is excellent, even in a somewhat noisy environment -- apparently the noise cancellation does work quite well.

The controls are easy to use: fortunately, they didn't go with the "one button for everything" that sounds clever but is impossible to use. There are separate buttons, well placed, for controlling power, volume, and call answer/disconnect. There is one multi-function button (under the boom) that is a mute button during a call, for streaming music pause/play, or for some voice action (speech recognition) commands at other times. If your phone supports it, you can also use the call control button to initiate voice dialing.

Another cool feature is call announcement: an incoming call is announced, with caller name (if supported by your phone), and you can say "answer" or "ignore". Or you can hit the call button if you're not the chatty type.

I also liked the charger: there is a magnetic coupling between the charging end of the headset and the charger, so they fit together securely. Nice thoughtful design there. Note however that the charging cable is very very short, just about 3 inches long. Go figure.

title: good quality case for droid 3, on the large side
text:
Since these cases aren't custom made for a specific phone model (this of course helps to keep the price down), I don't expect a perfect fit. So this is certainly quite acceptable for my Droid 3.

I was looking for a horizontal leather case with a belt clip, since I don't like carrying a phone in my pocket, especially not one as big & heavy as a Droid 3. The similar Krusell case that's slightly smaller seems just a few mm too small in the long dimension, so I opted for this one. The phone slips in and comes out quite easily, so that part is good. The belt loop is relatively slim (compared to some I've seen), and is comfortable to wear. It doesn't have a super-strong clip, so there is a slight risk of the case getting pulled off if it's caught on something (e.g., when you're getting in & out of your car).

The case is well-made, with a simple & solid construction. Overall a good choice if you're looking for a case for a large smartphone.

title: fair, but not great
text:
The case itself fits fine, and the iphone is certainly quite usable with the case on. I'm not doing any drop testing, but like some others I'm sceptical about the claims of impact protection.

I had a big problem with the clear screen protector -- it had little paper stickers on both sides (at the edge), that were to be pulled off before & after application. EXCEPT ... they were paper, and used cheap glue that didn't allow a clean peel-off, so the screen protector was basically useless. (Why is it that products made in China seem to only use cheap glue?) So that freebie ain't so great.

If I were to do it over, I'd probably go to a nearby discount store and get a cheapo silicone case for a couple of bucks less. But this does the job I wanted done, so I'm keeping it.

title: so far, quite excellent
text:
I was reluctant to buy this one, because I wasn't wholly satisfied with the Supertooth2 I had. However, excellent reviews in Cnet & other places, description of the features, and the limited choices of such products convinced me to give it a try.

So far I'm quite delighted, it has exceeded my expectations considerably. (I'd probably give it 4+ stars to be cautious, but I'm being generous, and will downgrade if experience justifies).

Firstly, the pairing was easy, once I figured out that my Samsung Renown (Verizon) didn't pair correctly if you had "Auto Pair" set. (Don't know who thought of that dumb feature.) And I was puzzled about the failure to download the phone book, until I read the Supertooth3 manual more carefully.

After that, everything worked smoothly, with no trouble. The sound is quite good, and the voice prompts and announcements are clear and concise. (I kept it on British English, since I liked that better than the US English.) All buttons are easily used, and conveniently placed.

Voice dialing through my phone worked reliably, consistently, and easily. Make sure you speak loudly and clearly, of course.

I love the readout of the caller-id, which is surprisingly fast, and very clear. Obviously a very useful feature when you're driving.

I also found the automatic re-connect feature very useful, and it does really work. (You leave your car to go into a store or something, the ST3 disconnects. When you get back in your car, the ST3 reconnects, and tells you politely that it did so.) The only thing I had to deal with was the manual disconnect at home, since the car in the garage is close enough that the ST3 won't disconnect until I move far enough away.

So, if you're looking for a bluetooth speakerphone for your car, this is a fine choice, and probably the best one out there.

title: works well, sound is a bit tinny (see update below)
text:
Works very well, I haven't had any problems with connectivity, voice dialing, volume, sensitivity, etc. I've used it in rush-hour driving, and it's quite usable despite the background noise. (Quite useful if you need to have a conference call from your car!) Battery life is fine as well.

On the downside, the sound is a bit tinny (metallic, thin, and harsh). But perhaps that's what you get for the price. And I do find it annoying that it takes a different kind of charger tip from my Razr, and Moto includes only the car charger with this package.

(Perhaps some day the manufacturers will figure out that they don't really gain anything by having all these variant charger interfaces, and will standardize on one? Nah.)

Update Sep18, 2007:
I've occasionally experienced some problems with this item in the time I've had it, thought this info might be useful if you're considering buying this.

One problem is an occasional "hang" when dialing -- you make a voice dial call, the phone says the name so you know it got the right number, but then nothing happens. Usually you give it a puzzled look after a few seconds, disconnect and try again, and everything works fine.

Sometimes however it's a real hang -- the phone's waiting for the device, the device is waiting for the phone (probably some piece of the bluetooth protocol got dropped on the floor), and you can't disconnect, you can't power the device down, nothing. You have to get your phone out and disconnect the device from the bluetooth menu, then recycle the power on the device, then you can proceed again. I haven't figured out why this happens, or a surefire way to prevent it. Doesn't happen a lot, but it shouldn't happen at all, right?

title: Bugs on device - phone field too short
text:
Just got the Sidekick II and spent literally an hour with tech support trying to get around a bug. They said nobody before had asked them that question. I call a lot overseas and, surely, don't dial directly due to the cost. I use a calling card, a pin and then the number. Even the oldest cell phones have a much longer field length on the phone number, so that you can program the calling card (10 digits), the pin (10 digits) and a foreign number (12+ digits). The Sidekick II stops on the 28th digit! What an annoyance. I found, however, that if I use the speed dial function, the field length is not restricted. With only 9 speed dials, though, this is not much help.

Another bug is that if you do a select-copy-paste on a phone, and copy the number to another speed dial (so I don;t have to type the calling card for every entry), it pastes the whole seeting, including the name and then doesn't let you change it.

A third bug is that the phone does not allow you to save a draft of a text message. If you are not able to send a message (system outage etc), you can't just save the message to send later, but you have to retype it.

Looks like the Sidekick II does not allow any change in color, plates or walpaper either.

I like the phone - it's fun and very intuitive, but at this time I am pondering whether to return it and stick with my Nokia 3650 which gives me all of the same, just without the bugs. I activated a new account with TMobile, but I have little hope they'll let me carry over my old number. My plan was just to cancel the old service..but I may give it a try if I keep the phone.

I wish these engineers didn't sleep on the job and stopped these annoying bugs from happening. After all, how hard is it to set a longer text field, if you are setting it on the speed dial anyway..

Oh...did I say the phone also doesn't allow you to add a memory card?

Good toy, though...I am nervous about putting work data on it, keeping in mind TMobile has access to it. Sure their servers are secure, but so are all banks...and they do have crackdowns from time to time..

So...still thinking about it..

title: I returned it for the Pixel 7--more RAM; better processing
text:
I tried to go budget with the 6a 128gb, but then I was dropping calls like it was the '90s; I had a 100% fail rate three calls in. After dialing *611, two transfers and like... 45 minutes, Verizon said it was because my sim card from my old phone was "incompatible," and they just remotely kicked me and my new phone off their network because they are incompetent. That gave me some time to reflect on the fact that I just needed more room and I /really/ didn't mind switching carriers for a locked phone deal and a sparkly new compatible sim.

I'm happy with my decision because I tend to leave lots of apps running and have lots of tabs in chrome, and even brand new, the 6a had a little trouble managing that. In particular, the developer options section in settings would lag and freeze, even when I was just scrolling through and had closed most other apps.

If you put your phone through a lot, consider going with the 7 or better for the processing capabilities. The only thing I preferred about the 6a was the slightly smaller size; I have smallish hands and it fit them better.

Also... if you're trying to decide whether to move your physical sim from your old phone or to download an e-sim, you should probably just go the e-sim route. Once I had a new sim (my new carrier sent me a physical one, so I just used that despite my younger sister's disdainful laugh at the thought), the Pixel 7 handled phone calls perfectly.

This morning, the numbers were the same and still flashing. My husband then noticed it said in very small letters "Out". So, we tried another block. This time, it said "In" so we left it to go. That was at about 10am. It is now EIGHT HOURS LATER and it has only climbed up 22%. In EIGHT HOURS. So I read the small details. It recommends a block with 5v/2a or 5v/2,4A power. I checked mine. It is 5v/.3 which is waay too weak for this (but works great with our phones). I checked another block here, it is 5v./1.55 I checked another. It is 5v/1a. So not one single block in our home is the recommended size for optimal charging. You would think the manufacture would INCLUDE a block specific to its needs.

Guess what we have go buy now.

Overall the pros outweigh the cons and the price is fair in my opinion. I feel confident that if I ever need to replace my case in the future, then I will most likely repurchase this case.

title: It's a long review, but it details my dismay.
text: I always prefer to write good reviews rather than bad ones but I had to put this out there. I purchased this pen in July 2018 after buying my Lenovo 730-15IKB. It worked fine when I got it, no issues at all as far as I remember. Now I'm no artist, but I thought I would have fun doodling with it, turns out pen and paper just feel better for me. After using it for a week or two I learned drawing on a computer wasn't what I thought it would be and stored the pen back in its box in my closet. The thing laid dormant and untouched in there until recently, in January 2020. I started studying again and thought the thing would work fine to take notes with at least. The tip and barrel buttons still work fine, but the bluetooth module on the back won't turn on at all. At first I thought it was that maybe the batteries had died and I spent $10 buying replacements (I stupidly bought the AAAA first because I thought it was the only battery, but realized only after replacing it that I needed the tiny SR527SW for the bluetooth module). Unfortunately replacing the batteries didn't work. The writing still works fine, but I wanted the bluetooth to work too so I could easily tap the back button to toggle between my note taking app and my online webinar app. If I had kept using it when I got it then I'm  sure I would have been able to replace when it decided to stop working. I'm not sure what the problem is, but I'm pretty sure some component got loose because the light won't turn on and I can hear a  I can hear a faint rattle. What upsets me the most is that I spent $10 on batteries I can't return and I don't have any other devices that use them. I feel confident I could probably fix the bluetooth module myself but I have no idea how to get to it without destroying the pen to get into it. Unfortunately it looks like no one else on the internet has taken it apart successfully to give me a guide either so I'm plum out of luck. For now I'm settling for using a partially functional pen, but for the price I expected it to have an operating life longer than the 50 hrs I actually used it for (and that's probably a generous estimate).

title: My Dream Wireless Charger
text:
I bought this product for my new Samsung S6 and I absolutely LOVE this wireless charger! :)

Usually, if something you pay for is cheaper than the original or something that is high quality (in this case, the Samsung wireless charger that costs $50), "you get what you pay for". Well, I am happy to say that is not the case. I really did take a chance on this product, and I am glad I did. I love how it is secure (non-slip whenever my phone is on it, unless you try to tilt it off enough, of course--then it will--because it is supposed to lay flat), how balanced the wireless charger is when it is a on flat surfaces, how it is non-slip on the bottom as well, it's lightweight for travel, and how it lights up & lets me know when it is on (RED), charging (BLUE pulsating) and done charging my phone (GREEN). Qi in Chinese means "light force" or "energy flow", so this product in real essence is of Qi, in terms of your phone. It really makes you feel like your phone is a living, breathing thing. Our phones are literally our lives after all, in this day and age.

Now, some people that reviewed this product on Amazon addressed some downsides: that this does not come with a USB wall adapter, that the wireless charger does not charge your phone fast enough and that it is lid up too much & bothers their eyes, especially while they try to sleep at night--Although it may NOT come with a USB wall adapter to keep this product on, it DOES come with a USB cord, in which you can connect with your regular Samsung USB wall adapter or a spare USB you have around. I think any wall adapter will work with this, as long as you have and can connect with a USB cord. I personally feel that the USB cord that this device comes with is a bit short from my nightstand so I just use my Samsung USB cord as well for extension. As for the charging, it does take a considerable amount of time to charge (about 2 hours or so, depending if you are the type that lets your phone go as close to 10% dying or charges it after 50% of battery life is lost) but that is still fast than perhaps other wireless chargers. Remember that most of the wireless chargers I browsed through here don't even light up at all like this one does. So consider the "slow" charging as an overstatement. It charges well enough. Still, if you have a busy lifestyle and use your phone from 9-5 like how your work schedule may be, this wireless charger is best used when you wind down for the night or you're better off using the traditional method.

The ONLY THING why I took a star off for is when it is supposedly done charging or when it immediately turned green when the very FIRST TIME I tested/used it, my phone was at 95%. It still charges but my point is that sometimes, it can make you believe it's fully charged when it may not be. It did also initially heat up my phone when beginner use but this has improved overtime and it works with a case on. Not so sure for metal phone cases. I wouldn't advise use of this product if you do because it will heat up your phone in the beginning (not sure why). But it is SAFE to use, and I love how it also serves as a nightlight for me, haha. Lights don't bother my eyes at night. But if you are the type of person that is sensitive to these kind of things, then this is also not the product for you. Take a chance on other brands but this is the best one for the value, price and convenience.

All and all, I am a happy customer! :)

title: Reliable charger for most electronics, but has a ground loop buzz with analog audio
text:
Like the title says - it charges most electrical devices at a decent rate. It does not seem compatible with various proprietary fast charging standards, but it also doesn't charge things slowly, it puts out plenty of power to top off devices even during use.

It feels very sold - it has some heft in the hand, the materials are dense and smooth, there is a pleasing matte finish to it. I'd like it to seat a bit better/more tightly in the cigarette lighter socket, but that may be the socket and not the charger.

My major complaint is that the power on this unit is not isolated, which means it is capable of creating a ground loop with analog audio devices, thus putting out a hum. This is disappointed for a device of this kind, even if analog audio is considerably more rare these days than it used to be. I have a much less expensive USB DC-DC buck converter which I tied in elsewhere in the car, and that does not have any such issue. Indeed this is how I know the noise is from the Anker - the exact same setup on the buck converter, which is connected to the same socket, has no issue were as the Anker has noise where ever it is connected. This necessitates the use of an isolator somewhere else in my setup.

If you don't care about the noise, then there's no problem, this is a good car charger. If noise is a potential problem, I'd look elsewhere or prepare to do your own isolation.

title: Great minimalist adapter for reducing cable clutter

If they had a Micro-USB version, I'd buy that too.

Charging is standard speed, if you are connected to an actual USB power supply. The adapter does not work for data transfer, or at least it didn't for me, so if that is what you are looking for I'd recommend getting an official Apple cable for $19.

These little adapters are a great way of avoiding the necessity of multiple wall warts.

These in particular are well-made, the sheathing feels high quality. Despite this, they add minimum bulk and weight, and they look like they belong on the end of the cable, especially if it is braided as well. Fit is snug on both ends, and charges as expected.

I might try to find a way to tether it to the end of the USB-C cable so it doesn't wander off.

No complaints from me, would recommend.

I use this pouch to stash my smartphone while I'm out on a hike. Normally I keep my phone in a waterproof pouch, but I also throw my keys, wallet, and various small pocket tools in there so I don't have the extra weight/bulk on me while I'm walking, bouldering, etc.. So I wanted something which would also protect it from being scratched or dinged. This is great - light, a little padded, plenty of space.

Maybe it could be a little stiffer, I'd feel better if it was just a little more rigid and indeed might insert a pair of plastic panels into it, just to ward against the odd impact. But this is mostly fine as it is.

Would recommend.

title: Decent stand for small to medium phones
text:
This works quite well for small to medium sized phones. I have a Motorola Moto X4 (5.82" x 2.89") in a slim case and it definitely fits on the stand, but its center of mass is just barely under the rear hinge of the cradle - much of the phone protrudes up over cradle's back-plate. This isn't a problem for stability - the two prongs on the cradle keep the phone from tipping back, and you can pivot the stand such balance is maintained - but if you have a larger phone you might find this not to be the case.

I plan on getting a smaller phone anyway, so it's not a problem, and the phone does stay put, it just doesn't "feel" very secure.

Build quality looks good, and the silicon pads feel quite grabby without being tacky. The stand isn't all that heavy but is made of substantial aluminum plates. The hinges have just the right amount of resistance so as move easily during repositioning but hold in place while the phone is resting.

I would probably recommend this to friends with phones a little smaller than my own.

title: Slim, flexible, decent coverage
text:
I purchased this for my Moto X4, and I am pretty happy with it. I like how it completely covers the side buttons, and how it has both a grippy bit on the back to keep the phone from sliding, and a smooth bit to make it move more readily in the hand. I haven't had any drops yet, but it certainly works as a bumper when the phone is in my pocket.

It is quite lightweight and quite thin - it barely increases the form-factor of the phone at all. It has some flex to it so it can absorb impacts and vibrations which is nice. It is just soft enough to offer some grip, but not so soft that its liable to sustain damage from daily activities.

If you live a rougher life, or are more careless with your phone, then this probably will not offer the protection you need - for that you'd want a full shell. However, if you aren't too active, or at least only bring your phone into relatively controlled environments like regular shopping, the office, the classroom, ect. this would probably work for you.

EDIT: I bought a magnetic mount for my car (SCOSCHE MPVB) and attached the metal plate to the inside of the case. It holds just fine. So this is thin enough to use with such a mount without needing to attach the plate to the outside.

title: A little delicate, but works well as a sacrifical screen protector
text:
I purchased these for my brand new Moto X4, along with a case. This model of phone isn't all that pricey, but I'd like to keep it in good shape anyway.

Installation was very easy - the rigidity of the protector makes it easy to install without bubbles of any kind. Just put the phone down in a clean, well-lit environment, wipe it down with the included alcohol pads, clean it off with the included microfiber cloth, line up the top or bottom edge and lay the protector down on the screen. Very simple.

The protector is oleophobic; this means that while it does accumulate fingerprints and such, it cleans off very easily. For example, I keep the protector in my suit jacket pocket, and its screen always comes out clean, no fingerprints at all. It is smooth and feels almost frictionless when using it with clean hands.

Visually, there is very little difference from the OEM screen, though this does have a fine but still visible grid of little dots. They don't bother me in the slightest, but I only use my phone for calls, texts, and checking email, and eschew all media-related activities. As such, it isn't a bother.

Durability-wise - well, I installed the protector and damaged it within a week, though the circumstances were pretty unique. The phone slid off the top of a jar and fell about a foot and a half and happened to catch the lip of a second jar on the way down. The impact point was exactly at the thinnest part of the protector, right below the aperture of the fingerprint scanner pad. This smashed, so that it is now whitish, but retained its form. There is a hairline crack that extends to the left across the bottom corner of the screen, but it is barely visible except in the proper light. I've kept the original protector on the phone and have had no further issues. No scratches either, though I'm pretty careful with it and so it rarely is in a position where it would be in contact with a significant abrasive.

Not bad. Maybe if I bought another, I'd get a thicker one, just to be sure, but I'm pretty happy with what I have here to be honest. Would recommend.

title: Seems like a good idea for a cell phone signal boost
text:
There are three main components to this signal booster. It's a good idea to take them all out and ensure you know what is what.

The first is the outdoor antenna. It's a white cone pyramid shape. This is what you want to setup outside and point towards a cell tower.

Second is the inside receiver unit. It's the black square box. This gets setup and connects the outdoor antenna to the indoor.

That's the third part. White circle. Indoor antenna. This is what completes the cycle to boost your cell phone signal.

The listing says that the major carriers have all provided blanket consent for these boosters but you also have to register it with the company. Give them a call and make sure you're good to go.

It has an app as well that seems cool. Let's you monitor and check out the stats.

title: The perfect get well soon gift
text: I bought this for my friend who recently had surgery.  I'm speaking from experience here and although flowers are nice, it's better to receive a get well soon present that is useful.  This is great for bedrest.  There's a compartment for your snacks that also has a lid.  There's also a wireless phone charger that allows you to charge your phone while still being able to use it.  If you lift up the charger or the snack compartment you can hide stuff like medicine or candy inside it.  The best part is the cup holder.  I'm not really sure how it works,  but it self balances.  You can try it knock it over and it just wiggles around.  This is especially helpful for her because she is still heavily medicated and her hands aren't very steady.
